04903nam a22007095i 9780585442051DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222001stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97805854420517 a10.1515/97805854420512doi  a(DE-B1597)615532  a(OCoLC)1312727388  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 4aPN56.D4 T36 2001 7aLIT0060002bisacsh04a809/.9335481 aTambling, Jeremy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBecoming Posthumous :bLife and Death in Literary and Cultural Studies /cJeremy Tambling. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2001  a1 online resource (176 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction The End/s of History -- tPart One Shakespeare's Opus Posthumous - Cymbeline -- tPart two Without Origins: David Copperfield -- tPart Three Ecce Homo: Nietzsche -- tPart Four Posthumous Shock: Walter Benjamin's History -- tAfterlife Ghostly Fathers/Unfathered Vapours -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGBS_insertPreviewButtonPopup('ISBN:9780748614776);Set against a backdrop of debates about the so-called 'end of history', 'the death of the subject' and 'the end of art', as well as the various forms of the 'post' that became prevalent in the late twentieth century, Jeremy Tambling introduces the idea of 'the posthumous' as a means of thinking about our relationship to the past, to death and to history.The trope of the posthumous is played out in a pattern of four deftly argued 'case-chapters' devoted to Shakespeare's Cymbeline (where the hero is Posthumus), Dickens's David Copperfield (a 'posthumous child'), Nietzsche's Ecce Homo (the record of a posthumous life) and Benjamin's 'Theses on the Philosophy of History' (where history comes into being posthumously). Using these texts as a launching point Professor Tambling provides readings concerned with the question of why we should give attention to history, and to past texts, if there has been an irretrievable 'break' with history, and where history has turned into the heritage industry.Discussing why many writers - Dante, Shakespeare, Jonson, Keats, Dickens, Nietzsche - have been fascinated by the idea of 'posthumous' existence and why post-Nietzschean critics such as Foucault, Derrida and de Man have thought in terms of the death of the subject, Professor Tambling sets out to discover whether the past is dead in relation to the present, or the present in relation to the past.Rigorous and astute in its critical insights, Becoming Posthumous also provides introductory readings of the critical theory of Walter Benjamin, Maurice Blanchot, Gilles Deleuze, Pierre Klossowski and Jacques Derrida. In showing how the idea of posthumous existence runs right through literary and cultural theory as well as major literary works, the book will be relevant to those who are interested in literature, history, and cultural studies, in theories of modernity, or the idea of 'living on', being a ghost, or just thinking about death and its relationship to life."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDeath in literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aDeath in literature. 0aLife in literature. 0aLiterature, Modern. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z97831107804680 cprintz978074861477640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978058544205140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780585442051423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780585442051/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  